    39	
    40	This paper does so in the unit health economists use to compare a death averted against years
    41	lived in better health: the quality-adjusted life-year. The exercise is deliberately in the style
    42	of a charity evaluator’s cost-effectiveness analysis (GiveWell 2026), scaled from a program to a
    43	portfolio, with one addition the setting forces: because most of the portfolio funds interventions
    44	whose health effects have never been causally measured, the model makes its epistemics explicit.
    45	Every effect is shrunk toward zero in proportion to how well its supporting study identifies
    46	causation, the shrinkage schedule is a slider rather than a buried constant, and the headline
    47	is reported across the full range of evidence philosophies — from counting only randomized
    48	evidence to taking every published estimate at face value.
    49	The paper makes four contributions. It provides, to my knowledge, the first portfolio-level
    50	cost-effectiveness estimate for a major philanthropist: a best-guess median of 202,000 QALYs
    51	from $26.39 billion nominal ($30.3B in 2026 dollars), a blended $150,067 per QALY, and a
    52	benefit–cost ratio of 4.9 at the U.S. government’s value per QALY (U.S. Department of Health
    53	and Human Services, Office of the Assistant Secretary for Planning and Evaluation 2026). It
    54	documents extreme geographic concentration of modeled impact: the 4.8% of dollars funding
    55	global health and development delivered outside the United States accounts for 69.1% of estimated
    56	health impact. It reports a new empirical regularity in the gift data itself: across 1,313 disclosed
    57	gift–filing pairs, gift size scales with recipient pre-gift revenue to the power 0.41 (R² 0.37) —
    58	Scott’s giving is far flatter across organization size than proportional. And it demonstrates a
    59	working method for auditable, AI-assisted cost-effectiveness modeling: the model was built with
    60	a frontier language model, reviewed and corrected in public across eleven revision rounds, audited
    61	by two independent model families against primary filings, and ships with versioned parameters,
    62	machine-checked citations, and a browser implementation that reruns the full Monte Carlo under
    63	any reader’s assumptions.
    64	The unit of account deserves a caveat before any number. QALYs measure health. Most of Scott’s
    65	portfolio aims at other things — education, economic mobility, equity, civic infrastructure —
    66	whose primary benefits are not health benefits. A finding that a dollar of education philanthropy
    67	produces few QALYs is a statement about the lens, not a verdict on the gift. The estimates here
    68	are a lower bound on total wellbeing produced, measured along the one dimension with a mature
    69	comparative literature.
