    81	2.2 Allocation across causes
    82	Scott publishes no aggregate dollars-by-cause breakdown, but she publishes better: a gift-level
    83	database listing every recipient organization, its self-reported focus areas, and — for 2,035 of 2,711
    84	gifts ($17.46B, about two-thirds of the nominal total) — the dollar amount. Each organization’s
    85	dollars are split equally across its focus areas; the database’s 53 areas map onto the model’s 14
    86	intervention archetypes under a documented, sync-tested crosswalk.
    87	The undisclosed third is imputed rather than dropped. Because the essays give each year’s
    88	total, the undisclosed residual per period is a known dollar amount; it is distributed across that
    89	period’s undisclosed gifts in proportion to each recipient’s pre-gift IRS Form 990 total revenue
    90	(ProPublica 2026), raised to an elasticity fit on the disclosed pairs. Pre-gift means the latest
    91	filing strictly before the gift year, since a Scott gift mechanically inflates receipt-year revenue.
    92	The fit is a finding in its own right: across 1,313 disclosed gift–filing pairs, log gift size rises
    93	with log revenue with slope 0.41 (R² 0.37). A 10× larger organization receives about 2.5× more
    94	money, not 10× more. Fuzzy name-to-EIN matches were audited by a third, smaller model
    95	against the live IRS API, with corrections committed as a reviewable overlay. The imputed third
    96	moves each cause share by at most about 1.5 percentage points — the disclosed two-thirds is
    97	representative.
