    99	2.3 Delivery geography
   100	Each organization reports service locations. Weighting disclosed dollars by the share of an
   101	organization’s locations outside the United States, an estimated 20% of disclosed dollars ($3.57
   102	billion of $17.46B) goes to organizations serving abroad, led by environment, health, and funding
   103	intermediaries. The model prices geography through a single channel: health-relevant dollars
   104	route to a global-health archetype in proportion to the recipient’s non-U.S. service share, because
   105	global health delivery is the one category with a published cost-per-QALY evidence base an
   106	order of magnitude below U.S. anchors. Education and climate dollars keep their U.S.-study
   107	anchors wherever they are delivered; if geography changes their effectiveness, the model does not
   108	capture it.
   109	The coarsest geographic field is the bare label “global.” An audit of the 50 largest organizations
   110	reporting only that label — 87% of that bucket’s dollars — replaced the blanket assumption of
   111	fully-abroad delivery with fractions taken from each organization’s own filings and program reports,
   112	independently verified by a second model family, with per-organization sources committed to the
   113	repository. Many “global” organizations operate substantially in the United States: Planned
   114	Parenthood and Crisis Text Line, for example, list “global” service but are roughly 95% and 93%
   115	U.S. by their own reporting. The audited allocation routes 4.82% of the ledger to global health
   116	and development delivered abroad.
