   119	Each Monte Carlo draw allocates the giving across archetypes (a Dirichlet centered on the
   120	derived shares), assigns each archetype a cost per QALY drawn from a distribution anchored in
   121	
   122	3
   123	
   124	published estimates, and multiplies the implied QALYs by two independent discounts. Causal
   125	credibility asks whether the measured effect is real. Each archetype carries the identification
   126	tier of its best supporting evidence, and the tier sets a Beta-distributed shrinkage factor toward
   127	the null: a lottery-randomized wealth shock (Cesarini et al. 2016) or the ACA Medicaid
   128	mortality quasi-experiment (Miller et al. 2021; Sommers 2017) keeps most of its effect; the
   129	community-health-center rollout design (Bailey and Goodman-Bacon 2015) and similar contested
   130	quasi-experiments keep less; associational and assumption-only categories are shrunk near zero.
   131	Realization asks whether a marginal philanthropic dollar delivers the studied effect at all —
   132	transport to different populations, overhead, and funging, net of the capacity effects of large
   133	unrestricted gifts that the Center for Effective Philanthropy documents for Scott’s recipients
   134	specifically (Center for Effective Philanthropy 2023). It is one global triangular draw with mode
   135	0.80 on support 0.55–1.10.
   136	The two discounts partition the doubt: transportability concerns live only in realization, identification concerns only in credibility, and cost-per-QALY priors are stated conditional on the
   137	effect being real and delivered. The tier ordering is the defensible part; the levels are judgment,
   138	proposed by a language model and reviewed by the author, and the results section reports the
   139	full consequence of disagreeing with them.
   140	Health effects arrive in different natural units — lives saved, life-years, depression-free days —
   141	and are converted to discounted QALYs under a common set of conventions (about 65 remaining
   142	life-years at baseline utility 0.87, 3% annual discounting), with every parameter’s unit and dollar
   143	vintage machine-validated at load. The global-health frontier benchmark is handicapped likefor-like: GiveWell’s current program averages (GiveWell 2026), converted to roughly $175–$241
   144	per discounted QALY-equivalent under this model’s own conventions, modeled as loguniform
   145	$150–$260, and subjected to the same realization and credibility discounts as Scott’s portfolio.
