paper/index.qmd:145:At the best-guess defaults (100,000 draws), the portfolio produces a median of `{python} F["median"]` QALYs, with a 90% interval of `{python} F["p05"]` to `{python} F["p95"]` and a mean of `{python} F["mean"]`. The blended cost-effectiveness — dollars given over QALYs produced, at the median — is `{python} F["blended"]` per QALY. Monetized at the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services' value per QALY, the health alone repays the giving 4.9 times over (90% interval 2.1–11.0). @fig-dist shows the full distribution.
paper/index.qmd:147:![Distribution of total QALYs across 100,000 Monte Carlo draws at the best-guess defaults. The dashed line marks the mean; the solid line the median.](../results/figure.png){#fig-dist}
paper/index.qmd:151:@tbl-cause decomposes the mean estimate by cause. The result is the paper's central contrast: the global health and development slice — `{python} F["abroad_share_1"]` of dollars — contributes `{python} F["gh_share"]` of estimated QALYs, at a realized cost of about $10,000 per QALY against $350,000–$450,000 for the large U.S. buckets. The 1,200-fold spread in realized cost-effectiveness within a single donor's portfolio is partly the lens speaking — its low end is dominated by assumption-tier buckets whose near-zero credibility is an input, and whose main benefits QALYs do not count — but the spread among evidenced health buckets alone exceeds an order of magnitude, restating in one column an empirical regularity long emphasized in the effective-altruism literature [@ord2013]: the cheapest health in the world is not bought where most philanthropic dollars are spent.
